DOCUMENT();
loadMacros('PGstandard.pl', 'PGML.pl', 'PGcourse.pl');

Context("LimitedNumeric"); 
Context()->strings->add("undefined"=>{}, "Does not exist"=>{alias=>'undefined'},"Not defined"=>{alias=>'undefined'});

$a = non_zero_random(-5,5);
$b = random(1,3);
@x = (random(-5,-1), 0, $b, $b + random(1,3,1));


BEGIN_PGML
For the equation, [` \displaystyle y = [$a] `], find the 
[`y`]-coordinate for each value of [`x`]. 

(Note: If a value is not defined, enter _Not defined_.)

[# [. [`x`] .] [. [`y`] .]*
   [. [`[$x[0]]`] .] [. [_]{Real($a)} .]*
   [. [`[$x[1]]`] .] [. [_]{Real($a)} .]*
   [. [`[$x[2]]`] .] [. [_]{Real($a)} .]*
   [. [`[$x[3]]`] .] [. [_]{Real($a)} .]*
   #]{align           => '|r|l|',
    horizontalrules => 1, padding => [0.25, 0.25]}

END_PGML

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
In this case, the function is just a constant, so the answer is [$a] for every value of [`x`]. 
END_PGML_SOLUTION

